  <h1>Core Empowering Coaching</h1>
  <p class="meta">Human-side AI fluency practice</p>

  <p>CEC is the human side of the Wuji Labs household. Where Wuji Labs Inc builds the AI collaboration spaces your team runs, CEC works with the people running them — and the people who haven't decided yet how they want to be with AI in the first place.</p>

  <p>CEC was the household's first practice. My partner and I went through iPEC's coaching program together — six months, ninety hours of formal instruction, nine full weekends — across 2023-2024, around the same time the workflow engine that became Playtiss began. We let the formal certification step go when our son was born in early 2025. The practice we did not let go of.</p>

  <p>The first axiom in iPEC training is: <strong>you cannot make a mistake.</strong> It is not a slogan, and it does not mean "consequences don't exist." It means that a state which diverged from intent is data about the world, not a moral indictment of the person who produced it. We practiced that axiom for ninety hours. It is the same axiom that, three years later, became <strong>L1.2 of the Collaboration Protocol — No Errors, Only Exceptions.</strong> Our son's name, 无忌 ("no fear / no error / unfettered"), names the same commitment. CEC and Wuji Labs Inc are two practices of one axiom.</p>

  <h2>Three modalities</h2>

  <p>CEC operates in three modalities. Each stands alone; each can stack with the others depending on what's actually needed.</p>

  <h3>Life &amp; Leadership Coaching (iPEC)</h3>

  <p>The original modality. iPEC-based life and leadership coaching for individuals, leaders, and teams. The work doesn't change because AI showed up — humans still grow with each other, and the practice of growing-with is older than any technology stack.</p>

  <p class="chip util"><span class="chip-tag">people ↔ people</span></p>

  <h3>AI-Relational Coaching</h3>

  <p>Coaching for the specifically modern problem: what is your relationship to AI, and how does that relationship shape what you can build, decide, or trust? Anxiety, groundedness, the felt-sense of working alongside something that isn't a tool but isn't a colleague either.</p>

  <p class="chip util"><span class="chip-tag">people → AI</span></p>

  <h3>AI-Tools Fluency Teaching</h3>

  <p>Hands-on Claude Code + agent-skill basics for individuals and teams. The teaching method is iPEC-shaped: a person learns to communicate with AI in the same way a person learns to communicate with another person. Not "here are 50 prompts that work." Closer to: "here is how to listen to what just happened, and adjust."</p>

  <p class="chip util"><span class="chip-tag">people ↔ people</span> <span class="chip-tag">people → AI</span></p>

  <h2>When CEC, when Wuji Labs, when both</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>CEC standalone</strong> — when the work is in the person or the relationship to AI itself, AND there's no engagement with Wuji Labs in the picture. iPEC life/leadership coaching for individuals or leaders, standalone AI-relational coaching, standalone AI-tools fluency teaching for individuals or small teams who want only the human-side work.</li>
    <li><strong>Wuji Labs engagement — with the human-side work bundled in</strong> — at an operator firm where the work is system design, Cosimo embeds, builds the collaboration space, AND provides AI-relational coaching + AI-tools training during the embed. One contract, one billing, one trust relationship. The household carries iPEC training on the system-side too — same training, same lineage, delivered by the founder who's already on-site.</li>
    <li><strong>iPEC coaching for the firm owner</strong> — never bundled. Different buying psychology (transformation, not ROI). Always a separate sale, always CEC. If discovery surfaces a leadership / clarity / decision-making issue for the owner that's not about AI, refer to CEC's iPEC modality directly.</li>
    <li><strong>The household commitment underneath</strong> — even when only one entity is engaged, the household stays connected through coaching-shaped discovery (validation, holding space, refer-out when it's not the right fit). The promise isn't <em>"you'll buy from both."</em> It's <em>"you'll be helped to figure out what would actually help — even if it's neither of us."</em></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>

  <p>For full information on offerings, scope, and rates — including how to book a discovery call — visit <a href="https://coreempowering.coach">coreempowering.coach</a>.</p>

  <p>For umbrella-level questions about how CEC and Wuji Labs Inc work together as a household practice, write to <a href="mailto:cosimo@wujilabs.dev">cosimo@wujilabs.dev</a>.</p>

  <hr />

  <p class="footnote"><em>Core Empowering Coaching LLC is co-founded and co-owned 50/50 by Cosimo and his partner in California. It is a legally separate entity from Wuji Labs Inc, sharing one philosophical claim and one household.</em></p>
